"2011 was the year that cyber-attacks hit the headlines. It seemed no one's reputation was safe from hackers and even cyber-defence companies suffered from massive security breaches. The spear-phishing attacks on security vendors RSA and DigiNotar were just two of the most serious examples. Private and public sector insiders have become one of the biggest risks to the security of critical data. And the more vital the information, the more sophisticated, targeted and frequent attacks are likely to be. This makes managing access to corporate or government resources more important than ever before. It's not enough to know who is accessing the network, and to verify that the user is approved to do so. A more thorough and detailed approach is required that combines access management with user activity monitoring, explains Marc Lee of Courion."
